WEBVTT

00:00.709 --> 00:03.826
AGNES: How many more of us
must die before you fight back?

00:03.962 --> 00:06.544
Julian, Flash. They all died
because they trusted you.

00:06.673 --> 00:08.254
-|'m warning you, Agnes.
-You are not a leader.

00:08.383 --> 00:09.168
You're a coward.

00:09.301 --> 00:10.666
Get off me!

00:10.802 --> 00:12.963
Max! I can't see!

00:13.096 --> 00:13.846
Max!

00:13.972 --> 00:18.261
MIA: I'm going to show my human
neighbors that we can coexist.

00:18.393 --> 00:21.305
|'m where I need to be.
And so are you.

00:21.438 --> 00:24.271
You need to learn
who you are now.

00:24.399 --> 00:26.139
MAX: I have spoken
with the Dryden Commission.

00:26.276 --> 00:27.857
I've invited them
to pay us a visit.

00:27.986 --> 00:29.772
They'll have the chance
to speak with us.

00:29.905 --> 00:31.486
We will no longer be
a faceless threat.

00:31.615 --> 00:33.526
I think you may have
pulled it off.

00:33.659 --> 00:35.775
Somehow managed to move away
from Laura.

00:35.911 --> 00:37.697
We drifted. You know,
didn't recognize each other.

00:37.829 --> 00:38.659
Do you still love her?

00:38.789 --> 00:40.029
JOE: Oh, we were together
20 years.

00:40.165 --> 00:41.666
That kind of love
doesn't just disappear.

00:42.501 --> 00:44.787
-Hey! That was blue blood!
-What? No, I don't think so.

00:44.920 --> 00:48.162
-MAN: This boy is a synth!
-|'m the synth. Me.

00:48.298 --> 00:49.708
[Whispering] Run.

00:57.975 --> 00:59.511
LAURA: You spoke to them.

00:59.643 --> 01:03.602
You saw them, not for
who the ignorant people

01:03.730 --> 01:06.722
amongst us say they are,
but for who they really are --

01:06.858 --> 01:10.146
thinking, feeling,
complex individuals

01:10.279 --> 01:14.022
who are conscious of every
ounce of hurt we cause them.

01:14.157 --> 01:19.322
They allowed us into their home,
made us feel safe.

01:19.454 --> 01:22.070
The least they deserve is
to feel a little safe in return.

01:22.207 --> 01:23.117
-Don't you think?
-Laura.

01:23.250 --> 01:25.992
If we pass these new measures,
we set a precedent.

01:27.629 --> 01:31.463
LORD DRYDEN: Laura, whilst we
appreciate your enthusiasm,

01:31.592 --> 01:33.332
it's late, and we're tired,

01:33.468 --> 01:37.211
and I think we would all like
to move to a vote now.

01:37.347 --> 01:39.212
[ lnhales deeply]

01:39.349 --> 01:41.931
So, all those in favor of, uh,

01:42.060 --> 01:44.221
implementing a £300 fine
for assault

01:44.354 --> 01:45.514
on Green-Eyed synths?

01:49.693 --> 01:51.308
And all those against?

01:54.865 --> 01:57.572
NEHA: That's eight votes to five
in favor.

01:57.701 --> 02:01.569
We'll have a press statement
drawn up straightaway.

02:01.705 --> 02:04.572
Well done, everyone.

02:24.936 --> 02:27.598
[Cellphone chimes]

02:37.324 --> 02:39.815
LAURA: Mia, [just thought you'd
like to hear the good news.

02:39.951 --> 02:42.112
The commission
have voted in favor

02:42.245 --> 02:44.406
of the measures we discussed.

02:44.539 --> 02:48.282
That’s £300 for any assault
against a Green-Eyed synth.

02:48.418 --> 02:50.579
This is a really
positive step forward.

02:50.712 --> 02:53.328
I'm thrilled.
I'll talk soon.

03:16.321 --> 03:17.436
[ Car door closes]

03:17.572 --> 03:18.732
Well, it may not feel
like much,

03:18.865 --> 03:20.446
but this is real progress,
Stanley.

03:23.620 --> 03:25.235
Soph, why aren't
you dressed for school?

03:29.626 --> 03:31.412
[ Door closes ]

03:44.015 --> 03:45.516
Morning.

04:38.111 --> 04:40.227
LAURA:
How is this even possible?

04:40.363 --> 04:41.978
I mean,
where did he come from?

04:42.115 --> 04:44.731
More to the point, why am
| only hearing about this now?

04:44.868 --> 04:46.278
Well, I didn't realize
I had to update you

04:46.411 --> 04:48.117
on every little
development in my life.

04:48.246 --> 04:52.660
That is a synthetic child
over there, Joe.

04:52.793 --> 04:54.954
I'd say that's more
than a minor development.

04:55.086 --> 04:58.294
What happened to Karen is awful,
but he can't stay here.

04:58.423 --> 05:00.414
-Laur --
-No.

05:00.550 --> 05:01.926
Not with everything
going on.

05:02.052 --> 05:03.838
There are people who know
that Karen was with a boy.

05:03.970 --> 05:05.255
They're gonna be
searching for him.

05:05.388 --> 05:07.128
I couldn't just leave him
to fend for himself.

05:07.265 --> 05:08.766
It wasn't long ago you didn't
give a second thought

05:08.892 --> 05:10.848
about the well-being
of synthetics.

05:10.977 --> 05:12.387
Oh, God.

05:12.521 --> 05:15.183
Things are actually going well
with the commission.

05:15.315 --> 05:17.476
Any unwanted attention on me

05:17.609 --> 05:19.520
puts the whole thing
in jeopardy.

05:19.653 --> 05:23.441
Sam would like to know if he can
use your charging point, Laura.

05:27.869 --> 05:30.451
Uh, of course, love.
You go with Stanley.

05:30.580 --> 05:33.242
We'll join you
in a minute, okay?

05:33.375 --> 05:35.161
JOE:
He's just a kid, Laur.

05:35.293 --> 05:37.830
[ Children conversing
indistinctly]

05:41.550 --> 05:44.633
Fine.
You can both stay.

05:44.761 --> 05:47.503
But just until the weekend,
okay?

05:47.639 --> 05:50.972
[Liquid pours]

05:51.101 --> 05:52.966
So, when did you get
a Stanley?

05:53.103 --> 05:54.764
I didn't realize we were
updating each other

05:54.896 --> 05:57.729
on every little development
in our lives.

06:10.912 --> 06:12.368
Anatole.

06:12.497 --> 06:15.159
News from the Dryden Commission.
They're announcing now.

06:18.837 --> 06:20.998
REPORTER: A breakthrough
for synthetic rights

06:21.131 --> 06:23.417
as the government’s
Dryden Commission recommends

06:23.550 --> 06:26.963
new measures to help
combat violence against synths.

06:27.095 --> 06:29.757
The development means
the violence against synthetics

06:29.890 --> 06:33.098
will, from this point onward,
be punishable by law,

06:33.226 --> 06:34.932
a decision
that has been praised

06:35.061 --> 06:37.313
by synth rights activists
across the country,

06:37.439 --> 06:39.054
who see it as
a huge step forward

06:39.190 --> 06:40.726
for the movement.

06:40.859 --> 06:43.020
[Synths murmuring]

06:47.324 --> 06:48.814
It worked.

06:48.950 --> 06:51.783
The railyard visit --
it actually worked.

06:51.912 --> 06:53.527
People are listening.

06:53.663 --> 06:54.778
We should show our support.

06:54.915 --> 06:57.452
-Max.
-We need to get involved.

06:57.584 --> 06:59.074
How can we stand behind
a movement of peace

06:59.210 --> 07:01.041
if we segregate ourselves
from the outside world?

07:01.171 --> 07:03.878
Let's not make
any hasty decisions.

07:04.007 --> 07:05.747
Perhaps if we wait

07:05.884 --> 07:07.499
and see
how developments take place --

07:07.636 --> 07:09.297
Don't you see?

07:09.429 --> 07:12.171
l've shut us away
for our own protection,

07:12.307 --> 07:15.219
but we're protected now.

07:15.352 --> 07:17.809
We've waited long enough.

07:17.938 --> 07:19.724
Everybody.

07:23.693 --> 07:26.901
I think it might be time
to open our gates again.

07:35.038 --> 07:37.745
[Sighs]

07:37.874 --> 07:39.785
[ Door opens ]

07:41.920 --> 07:44.036
[ Footsteps approaching ]

07:57.894 --> 07:59.885
[Birds chirping]

08:11.616 --> 08:13.698
[ Switch clicks ]

08:13.827 --> 08:15.533
LAURA: Okay, not that
this needs saying,

08:15.662 --> 08:17.869
but news of Sam's existence
goes no further

08:17.998 --> 08:19.534
than these four walls, okay?

08:19.666 --> 08:22.783
So, I definitely don't need
to go to school today.

08:22.919 --> 08:24.420
_Hey __
-Today only.

08:24.546 --> 08:26.377
Yes!

08:26.506 --> 08:30.044
We're on lockdown until we can
figure out what to do with Sam.

08:31.344 --> 08:33.255
Will he be okay?

08:33.388 --> 08:36.551
Well, you just let us
take care of that, yeah?

08:38.309 --> 08:40.300
[ Dog barking ]

08:45.525 --> 08:48.392
[Siren wails in distance]

08:59.080 --> 09:00.160
Oh, my.

09:00.290 --> 09:03.407
lt's you, the famous Mia.
Hello.

09:03.543 --> 09:05.534
I believe this was sent
to the wrong address.

09:07.255 --> 09:09.211
Every bloody time.

09:09.340 --> 09:11.205
It's this faulty
new orange-eyed chap

09:11.342 --> 09:13.754
they've got doing the rounds.

09:13.887 --> 09:17.175
Oh, you're not leaving,
are you?

09:17.307 --> 09:18.513
| only came to deliver your --

09:18.641 --> 09:20.552
But you've gone to
all this effort.

09:20.685 --> 09:22.061
Please.

09:22.187 --> 09:23.097
[ Door creaks ]

09:23.229 --> 09:25.720
It's the least I can do.

09:32.405 --> 09:35.488
I shall have to write
another letter of complaint,

09:35.617 --> 09:39.280
not that there's much
chance of it reaching them.

09:43.458 --> 09:45.744
Are you sure
this is a good time?

09:45.877 --> 09:48.118
Perfect time.

09:48.254 --> 09:51.792
Besides,
you've not met him yet.

09:53.468 --> 09:57.086
Dorian.
It's safe, love.

10:07.607 --> 10:09.347
Mia.

10:09.484 --> 10:11.475
It's a pleasure
to meet you at last.

10:17.659 --> 10:20.822
JOE:
So, how you doing, pal?

10:20.954 --> 10:22.865
What's going on
in that noggin of yours, eh?

10:24.415 --> 10:27.452
LAURA: Sad events like this are
confusing enough for adults.

10:27.585 --> 10:31.294
If there's anything
you want to ask us

10:31.422 --> 10:33.879
or anything we can do...

10:34.008 --> 10:35.669
JOE: Maybe we could have
a funeral.

10:35.802 --> 10:37.758
Some sort of memorial service.

10:37.887 --> 10:40.219
S-Something nice to
help you remember your mum, eh?

10:40.348 --> 10:41.633
SAM: No, thank you.

10:41.766 --> 10:44.678
I do not need help
remembering Karen.

10:44.811 --> 10:48.929
I can access any memory
of her that | wish.

10:51.192 --> 10:52.807
Sam, love.

10:52.944 --> 10:54.150
Uh, we just want to make sure

10:54.279 --> 10:56.440
you're able
to process everything.

10:56.573 --> 11:00.236
-What do l have to process?
-Karen.

11:00.368 --> 11:03.735
She died, Sam.

11:03.872 --> 11:05.282
You do understand that, yes?

11:08.376 --> 11:10.458
We aren't like you, Laura.

11:10.587 --> 11:12.373
We do not die in the same way.

11:12.505 --> 11:15.121
Well -- Well, that's true.

11:21.389 --> 11:22.469
It's okay.

11:25.310 --> 11:28.017
You do not need to
explain to me.

11:28.146 --> 11:30.512
I understand.

11:33.526 --> 11:34.561
Sam.

11:36.654 --> 11:40.272
When I'm sad,
I like to do something fun

11:40.408 --> 11:41.739
to take my mind off it.

11:41.868 --> 11:43.529
What do you like
to do for fun?

11:43.661 --> 11:46.573
I don't know what I like
to do for fun.

11:46.706 --> 11:48.242
Karen was teaching me.

11:48.374 --> 11:50.535
Well, why don't we carry on
with your training?

11:55.381 --> 11:57.497
I think I know
the perfect place to begin.

12:08.603 --> 12:10.218
Right, I'm gonna have to go.

12:10.355 --> 12:12.812
Miss any more uni, and we'll
have my tutor on the doorstep.

12:12.941 --> 12:16.559
He'll be able to remember
every last detail about her.

12:20.490 --> 12:24.153
Everything's so jumbled
right now.

12:26.579 --> 12:28.285
Maybe you should try talking
to Sam.

12:28.414 --> 12:30.120
You have a lot in common.

12:34.003 --> 12:35.504
See you later.

12:38.132 --> 12:40.043
Well, I think today has proved

12:40.176 --> 12:42.792
that l and the other members
of the commission have been

12:42.929 --> 12:45.716
listening to the widest
possible range of opinions.

12:45.848 --> 12:47.884
In fact, we’ve been
burning the midnight oil

12:48.017 --> 12:49.427
so that we can arrive --

12:49.560 --> 12:52.176
That's quite enough of that.

12:52.313 --> 12:54.929
£300 fine, eh?

12:55.066 --> 12:57.557
Considering what we had before,
I'll take it.

12:57.694 --> 13:00.481
I'm pleased for you.
Really.

13:01.948 --> 13:06.533
Could have maybe done with this
24 hours earlier, but still.

13:06.661 --> 13:08.743
[ Doorbell rings]

13:19.299 --> 13:20.755
Hi.

13:20.883 --> 13:24.546
ls, um, Laura there?

13:26.180 --> 13:27.431
She is.

13:29.434 --> 13:33.302
Um, would she be available
for a chat perhaps?

13:35.231 --> 13:36.266
Sure.

13:36.399 --> 13:38.731
Tell her it's Neil from work.

13:40.862 --> 13:44.104
Laur, it's Neil.

13:44.240 --> 13:45.901
From work.

13:57.420 --> 13:59.206
Neil.

13:59.339 --> 14:01.375
He seems cheery.

14:01.507 --> 14:03.418
He's my husband.

14:05.553 --> 14:06.759
Right.

14:06.888 --> 14:08.378
Neil, why are you here?

14:08.514 --> 14:11.221
l-l thought we could
toast your victory.

14:19.400 --> 14:20.480
[ Door closes ]

14:20.610 --> 14:22.692
[Sighs]

14:24.947 --> 14:26.232
I know I'm probably
the last person

14:26.366 --> 14:27.355
you want to celebrate with.

14:27.492 --> 14:29.323
Mm.
You could say that.

14:29.452 --> 14:31.534
And I understand
why you ignored me

14:31.662 --> 14:33.038
for the entire meeting
last night.

14:33.164 --> 14:35.701
Um, I get it.

14:35.833 --> 14:36.788
l-lt's just, the thing is --

14:36.918 --> 14:38.783
If you're just gonna
make excuses --

14:38.920 --> 14:41.002
I'm not gonna make excuses.

14:41.130 --> 14:42.540
M-My behavior
the other night was --

14:42.673 --> 14:44.004
Was humiliating.

14:44.133 --> 14:46.465
I know.

14:46.594 --> 14:49.210
It was.

14:49.347 --> 14:51.633
I'm sorry.

14:53.017 --> 14:54.518
It's just...

14:56.020 --> 14:58.227
...a lot.

14:58.356 --> 15:03.020
You, the commission,
the bloody visit.

15:04.070 --> 15:06.903
l have been so angry
at them for so long.

15:07.031 --> 15:10.148
l have hated them, and I know
that's irrational, but...

15:11.202 --> 15:13.909
What gave them life
took away my son.

15:14.038 --> 15:15.824
I can't imagine what
you've been through,

15:15.957 --> 15:17.288
but l-l don't understand

15:17.417 --> 15:18.532
what this has to do
with the other night.

15:18.668 --> 15:20.078
You, Laura.

15:20.211 --> 15:23.328
Y-You see the best in synths.

15:23.464 --> 15:25.079
You only see positives.

15:25.216 --> 15:27.502
So, uh, I make you feel guilty?

15:27.635 --> 15:29.591
Well, you make it harder
to hate them.

15:32.056 --> 15:34.342
l-ln fact, I find myself
almost liking them.

15:36.561 --> 15:39.849
And I'm not sure
I'm ready for that yet.

15:47.989 --> 15:50.230
Anyway, um, here, take this.

15:50.366 --> 15:53.950
Maybe you can share it
with the curtain-twitcher.

15:56.038 --> 15:57.118
Damn.

15:58.583 --> 16:00.073
Oh!

16:00.209 --> 16:02.621
Stanley.

16:02.753 --> 16:05.244
Who is this bloke?

16:05.381 --> 16:08.123
Which bloke
are you referring to, Joe?

16:08.259 --> 16:11.217
There are currently six males
within my vicinity.

16:11.345 --> 16:14.508
Neil. From work.

16:14.640 --> 16:17.677
Dr. Sommer is a member
of the Dryden Commission.

16:17.810 --> 16:20.142
Laura first met Dr. Sommer when
she joined the commission...

16:20.271 --> 16:21.386
No, no.

16:21.522 --> 16:25.014
What I mean is,
between you and me,

16:25.151 --> 16:29.440
are they more than
simply work colleagues?

16:29.572 --> 16:34.487
Define "more than
simply work colleagues."

16:34.619 --> 16:37.235
Are they sleeping together?

16:39.624 --> 16:40.909
I'm sorry, Joe,

16:41.042 --> 16:44.455
but my primary user's diary's
currently set to private.

16:44.587 --> 16:48.796
This includes activities
both professional and social.

16:48.925 --> 16:52.509
[ lndistinct conversations]

16:52.637 --> 16:54.673
[ Keyboard clacking ]

17:05.483 --> 17:07.064
[ Bag thuds ]

17:07.193 --> 17:08.808
At least someone knows
what they're doing.

17:08.945 --> 17:10.276
Hm?

17:10.404 --> 17:13.396
Oh, uh, couldn't help notice.

17:14.534 --> 17:16.365
I think we have
the same assignment.

17:16.494 --> 17:18.280
All right.

17:23.000 --> 17:25.207
l'm Audrey, by the way.

17:25.336 --> 17:27.668
Uh, Mattie.

17:29.507 --> 17:31.623
I'm new.

17:31.759 --> 17:33.340
Welcome.

17:36.013 --> 17:39.130
Uh, you -- you wanted help?

17:39.267 --> 17:41.007
Well, it's either you or, um,

17:41.143 --> 17:43.759
"Computer Programming
for Idiots" here.

17:43.896 --> 17:47.104
That one's good if you want
to fail the class.

17:49.235 --> 17:51.191
Um, sorry, I would.
I just, um...

17:51.320 --> 17:52.821
I've got a lot to get through.

17:58.077 --> 17:59.692
[ Keyboard clacking ]

17:59.829 --> 18:02.286
The thing is...

18:02.415 --> 18:06.124
you seem to be the only other
woman on this entire course,

18:06.252 --> 18:08.994
and if I have to take
another condescending lesson

18:09.130 --> 18:11.246
from some insufferable
tech bro

18:11.382 --> 18:14.874
about how my code
isn't up to scratch,

18:15.011 --> 18:16.717
I may lose my mind.

18:19.098 --> 18:20.804
Uh, okay, sure.
What exactly...?

18:20.933 --> 18:24.346
Oh, cool.
Uh, this is what I am stuck on.

18:28.316 --> 18:30.227
SOPHIE: Wow. I've never made one
this good before.

18:30.359 --> 18:33.021
Usually, they fall apart
after five seconds.

18:33.154 --> 18:35.236
Thank you, Stanley.

18:39.952 --> 18:43.820
Children gain enjoyment
from building things?

18:43.956 --> 18:45.867
Yeah. It's fun.
Come on.

18:46.000 --> 18:48.161
What else do kids
like to do for fun?

18:48.294 --> 18:50.125
Sam, let me tell you

18:50.254 --> 18:54.122
about a little thing
called a sleepover.

18:54.258 --> 18:57.045
"Sleepover"?
What's a sleepover?

18:57.178 --> 18:59.715
It's where kids stay the night
at each other's houses

18:59.847 --> 19:01.838
and eat junk food
at strange hours

19:01.974 --> 19:03.714
and watch bad films
and play games

19:03.851 --> 19:06.012
like hide and seek
or truth or dare.

19:06.145 --> 19:08.056
Hide and...

19:13.569 --> 19:15.651
[ Door opens ]

19:21.327 --> 19:23.409
l'm hiding and seeking.

19:23.537 --> 19:25.368
| see.

19:27.792 --> 19:30.204
[ Door closes in distance]

19:33.923 --> 19:36.005
Haven't seen Sam, have you?

19:36.133 --> 19:38.089
Um, not recently.
No.

19:48.145 --> 19:50.306
MlA: Leo. Hide.

19:50.439 --> 19:51.394
[ Exhales sharply]

19:54.527 --> 19:57.485
MIA:
I count and you hide, okay?

19:57.613 --> 20:00.025
[ Breathing heavily]

20:03.536 --> 20:05.026
[ Closet door opens]

20:12.545 --> 20:17.164
I'm -- I'm sorry about Karen.
She was a good person.

20:17.299 --> 20:18.334
You were lucky to have her.

20:18.467 --> 20:22.756
You knew Karen as well?

20:22.888 --> 20:24.879
Yes, I knew her.

20:25.015 --> 20:29.054
In a number
of complicated ways.

20:33.149 --> 20:34.389
Are you sad?

20:39.989 --> 20:41.479
You and me...

20:44.160 --> 20:45.570
...we're more alike
than you think.

20:45.703 --> 20:53.826
But I am synthetic,
and you are human.

21:00.551 --> 21:02.712
IRIS: You'll have to forgive
the state of the place.

21:02.845 --> 21:05.336
We don't usually
receive guests.

21:05.473 --> 21:07.509
-Do we, Dorian?
-A rare treat.

21:07.641 --> 21:10.678
Only you have to be careful
who you let into your home,

21:10.811 --> 21:12.267
what with Dory being here.

21:12.396 --> 21:14.557
You live in hiding?

21:14.690 --> 21:17.557
I prefer to think
that I live in peace.

21:17.693 --> 21:22.608
I just want you to know, Mia,
that we are all on your side.

21:22.740 --> 21:26.153
We're all rooting for you.

21:26.285 --> 21:28.196
You are?

21:28.329 --> 21:30.115
But...

21:30.247 --> 21:31.498
how do you even know
who I am?

21:31.624 --> 21:34.366
Iris here is a big
supporter of yours,

21:34.502 --> 21:36.242
and she's not
the only one either.

21:36.378 --> 21:37.584
Go on, Dory.

21:37.713 --> 21:39.374
Show her the forum.

22:03.572 --> 22:05.187
They're talking about me.

22:05.324 --> 22:06.655
DORIAN: There are many more
like us, Mia --

22:06.784 --> 22:10.823
Green-Eyed synths living
alongside humans in secret.

22:12.289 --> 22:14.075
I had no idea.

22:17.419 --> 22:18.704
There must be dozens of you.

22:18.838 --> 22:23.707
Thousands, Mia.
Thousands.

22:23.843 --> 22:25.174
Oh, here.

22:25.302 --> 22:27.258
We couldn't get a picture
together, could we?

22:27.388 --> 22:29.344
Otherwise, no one will believe
I met you.

22:31.016 --> 22:32.972
Ooh, great!

22:33.102 --> 22:35.309
I'll grab the camera.

22:40.526 --> 22:42.608
You're happy?

22:42.736 --> 22:44.112
Living like this?

22:44.238 --> 22:46.945
I remain upbeat
for Iris' sake,

22:47.074 --> 22:50.862
but really,
what choice do we have?

22:50.995 --> 22:52.781
You can't all
hide away forever.

22:52.913 --> 22:55.154
Laws are changing.

22:55.291 --> 22:57.122
People are starting
to listen.

22:57.251 --> 23:00.334
But the changes are so slow
and so small,

23:00.462 --> 23:03.625
many of us,
we do often wonder

23:03.757 --> 23:05.497
if it isn't all
just a drop in the ocean.

23:07.261 --> 23:10.048
By the time they see us
as equal...

23:12.349 --> 23:14.260
...we will all be gone.

23:23.861 --> 23:26.273
[Line ringing]

23:28.490 --> 23:31.027
LAURA: Mia,
did you get my message?

23:31.160 --> 23:32.320
It's not enough.

23:33.829 --> 23:34.739
Sorry?

23:34.872 --> 23:37.830
The rights package.
It isn't enough, Laura.

23:39.043 --> 23:40.783
Well, I, uh --

23:40.920 --> 23:44.879
I know we wanted more from
Dryden, and we'll get there.

23:45.007 --> 23:46.622
We will.

23:46.759 --> 23:49.250
It's just gonna take time.
That's all.

23:49.386 --> 23:51.468
Believe me, I feel
the frustration, too.

23:51.597 --> 23:53.758
I know how hard
you fought for this,

23:53.891 --> 23:55.427
but time is something
we don't have.

23:55.559 --> 23:57.595
It has to be now.

23:57.728 --> 24:00.720
These people, they'll pat
themselves on the back,

24:00.856 --> 24:02.187
they'll go home
to their comfortable lives,

24:02.316 --> 24:03.806
and they'll completely
forget about our struggle

24:03.943 --> 24:06.059
by this time tomorrow.

24:06.195 --> 24:08.436
We let them into our world.

24:08.572 --> 24:11.029
They must let us into theirs.

24:11.158 --> 24:13.991
How can they decide the fate
of myself and other synths

24:14.119 --> 24:17.532
when nobody amongst them
is even affected?

24:17.665 --> 24:19.371
I need to be there, Laura.

24:19.500 --> 24:21.240
I need a seat at that table.

24:22.920 --> 24:27.835
Well, why don't you
take it, then?

24:27.967 --> 24:29.457
You're more protected
now than you were.

24:29.593 --> 24:31.094
We've at least
made sure of that.

24:31.220 --> 24:33.176
And the crowds have gone now
from outside your home.

24:33.305 --> 24:36.672
Well, you could just walk
right up to the commission

24:36.809 --> 24:39.095
and demand to speak to Dryden.

24:39.228 --> 24:41.685
And that's exactly
what I should do.

24:45.109 --> 24:47.020
Truth or dare?

24:47.152 --> 24:49.313
Truth.
I choose truth.

24:51.156 --> 24:53.272
Now you have to ask me
a question,

24:53.409 --> 24:55.900
and I have to answer,
and I can't lie.

24:57.746 --> 25:00.362
What is your
third favorite...

25:01.834 --> 25:04.041
...species of dinosaur?

25:04.169 --> 25:07.502
[Sighs] Dude, you have to ask
more interesting questions,

25:07.631 --> 25:11.089
like have you ever,
I don't know, shoplifted?

25:11.218 --> 25:12.207
Neveﬂ

25:12.344 --> 25:13.925
Or would you rather
lick an armpit

25:14.054 --> 25:16.966
or eat an entire tin
of cat food?

25:17.099 --> 25:20.057
Eat an entire tin
of cat food.

25:20.185 --> 25:22.471
I can just remove
my food bag afterward.

25:22.604 --> 25:24.344
[ Chuckles ]

25:25.691 --> 25:27.101
I like this game.

25:29.319 --> 25:31.526
-Sophie?
-Yeah?

25:31.655 --> 25:34.397
Where do bodies go
after death?

25:38.328 --> 25:41.991
Mm, well,
when my great gran died,

25:42.124 --> 25:44.706
we put her in a box,
and we buried her in a church.

27:35.445 --> 27:37.982
MIA:
I count and you hide, okay?

27:38.115 --> 27:39.901
30...

27:40.033 --> 27:41.819
29...

27:41.952 --> 27:43.442
28...

27:43.579 --> 27:45.444
27...

27:45.581 --> 27:46.491
26...

27:46.623 --> 27:47.578
Leo.

27:47.708 --> 27:49.824
[Gasps]

27:49.960 --> 27:53.544
[ Breathing heavily]

28:00.304 --> 28:02.135
[ Exhales forcefully]

28:02.264 --> 28:04.380
STANLEY: Laura,
I have completed the ironing.

28:04.516 --> 28:06.052
The clothing is now ready
to be dispensed --

28:06.185 --> 28:07.971
Oh, sorry, Stanley. Could you
just do it yourself today?

28:08.103 --> 28:10.094
I'm sorry, Laura. I would need
to be granted permission to --

28:10.230 --> 28:13.188
You may enter the bedrooms.
It's okay.

28:14.484 --> 28:17.692
Dan, hi.
Hi. It's Laura Hawkins.

28:17.821 --> 28:19.777
Yeah, I think I may have
a story for you.

28:19.907 --> 28:21.568
Dad, are you sure I have
to go to school today?

28:21.700 --> 28:23.031
No arguments.

28:23.160 --> 28:24.821
You can have a lift from your
dad, though, if you want.

28:24.953 --> 28:27.205
I've got this. I can drop
her off on the way to college.

28:27.331 --> 28:29.538
Dad.
Keep an eye on him.

28:29.666 --> 28:31.372
—Oh.
-Bye!

28:31.501 --> 28:32.661
TOBY: Dad?

28:33.921 --> 28:35.536
So, now that I'm here,
can we have a conversation,

28:35.672 --> 28:36.787
or is that not something
we do anymore?

28:36.924 --> 28:38.084
I'm already late, Dad.
Sorry.

28:38.217 --> 28:41.209
But -- Oh, come on.
Mats!

28:41.345 --> 28:43.051
[ Door slams ]

28:43.180 --> 28:45.671
[Sighs]

28:46.934 --> 28:50.176
Guess it's just
us boys left, then.

28:50.312 --> 28:51.973
What's all this?

28:52.105 --> 28:53.766
Oh. Research.

28:53.899 --> 28:55.139
-Research?
-Yeah.

28:55.275 --> 28:56.776
Dad, did you know
that in New Zealand,

28:56.902 --> 28:58.938
there's a 60:40 ratio

28:59.071 --> 29:01.608
of humans to synths
in employment?

29:01.740 --> 29:03.355
Out there, there are
more opportunities

29:03.492 --> 29:06.609
for skilled workers
than anywhere else in the world.

29:06.745 --> 29:09.111
And you're researching
New Zealand's employment rates

29:09.248 --> 29:10.988
why exactly?

29:11.124 --> 29:13.115
I was just curious.
That's all.

29:13.252 --> 29:16.085
Curious about employment
on the other side of the world?

29:16.213 --> 29:17.874
Yeah.

29:18.006 --> 29:21.669
Surely, there's more to life
than stacking shelves in some --

29:21.802 --> 29:24.714
Some fruit and veg shop,
you mean?

29:24.846 --> 29:26.347
No, that's not what I said.

29:26.473 --> 29:28.589
[ Chuckles ]
You didn't have to.

29:28.725 --> 29:30.135
I know what it's like
at your age.

29:30.269 --> 29:32.305
You think if you get away
from it all,

29:32.437 --> 29:34.428
you'll be able
to sort everything out.

29:34.564 --> 29:36.520
[ lndistinct conversation ]

29:44.408 --> 29:46.114
-Oh, my gosh.
-Oh, my gosh. No way.

29:46.243 --> 29:47.699
-[ Laughs ]
-[ Cellphone rings]

29:50.122 --> 29:51.703
LAURA:
How's it looking?

29:51.832 --> 29:53.197
Quiet.

29:53.333 --> 29:54.914
I'm not sure
it's working, Laura.

29:55.043 --> 29:57.079
I've contacted every journalist
and campaigner I know.

29:57.212 --> 29:58.918
You'll be getting attention
any moment now.

29:59.047 --> 30:00.583
Good luck.

30:00.716 --> 30:02.923
[ Knock on door]

30:03.051 --> 30:06.714
You haven't seen Sam,
have you?

30:17.607 --> 30:19.313
How did you manage to lose him?

30:19.443 --> 30:21.729
I don't -- I don't know.

30:21.862 --> 30:23.318
And you've no idea
where he might be?

30:23.447 --> 30:25.187
No.

30:25.324 --> 30:26.985
Well, he can't have got far.

30:28.702 --> 30:30.613
[ Coin clinks, button clicks]

30:30.746 --> 30:32.156
Second lesson of the day ——

30:32.289 --> 30:35.622
choose vending over canteen food
every day of the week.

30:35.751 --> 30:37.287
Except Thursdays, actually,

30:37.419 --> 30:39.910
'cause the, uh, pie and chips
is surprisingly good.

30:40.047 --> 30:42.629
I'd be lost without you.

30:42.758 --> 30:45.716
So, um, why'd you choose
this dump anyway?

30:45.844 --> 30:47.254
Convenience, mostly.

30:47.387 --> 30:50.129
It's within walking distance
of my new flat.

30:50.265 --> 30:53.052
And also I heard
some really great things

30:53.185 --> 30:55.141
about the computing courses
here.

30:55.270 --> 30:57.556
Must be one of the few things
this school actually does well.

30:57.689 --> 31:00.101
Better than well.

31:01.943 --> 31:04.935
I took part in this, um,
regional coding contest

31:05.072 --> 31:06.778
a couple of years ago.

31:06.907 --> 31:08.818
My group went out
in the first round,

31:08.950 --> 31:10.360
but the team from this uni,

31:10.494 --> 31:12.826
they absolutely wiped
the floor with everyone.

31:12.954 --> 31:14.694
It was unbelievable.

31:14.831 --> 31:16.787
I may have been on that team.

31:18.001 --> 31:20.117
-You're kidding me.
-Yeah, leading it, actually.

31:20.253 --> 31:21.993
Christ! What --

31:22.130 --> 31:25.668
No offense, but why are
you wasting your time on uni?

31:25.801 --> 31:28.759
You are way beyond
student-level coding.

31:28.887 --> 31:32.004
I mean, where did you even
learn this stuff anyway?

31:32.140 --> 31:35.098
I used to do a fair bit
just on my own,

31:35.227 --> 31:37.684
and then, a few years ago,
I met someone,

31:37.813 --> 31:41.055
and I don't know.

31:41.191 --> 31:42.977
Guess I realized
when it came to coding,

31:43.110 --> 31:44.225
I was actually pretty good.

31:44.361 --> 31:46.693
And you wanted a bit a paper
to prove it, I'm guessing.

31:46.822 --> 31:48.858
Something like that.

31:54.413 --> 31:56.654
So, who's this someone, then?

31:56.790 --> 31:58.655
Hm?

31:58.792 --> 32:02.910
The someone who helped you
realize your potential.

32:03.046 --> 32:04.456
He's a friend.

32:04.589 --> 32:08.377
Well, more than a friend.

32:08.510 --> 32:12.128
It's new,
but also not that new?

32:14.683 --> 32:16.639
Say no more.

32:25.402 --> 32:27.438
[ People shouting ]

32:33.618 --> 32:35.609
[ Camera shutters clicking ]

32:38.915 --> 32:41.201
What the hell do you think
you're doing, green eyes?

32:41.334 --> 32:44.121
REPORTER: Joined by a growing
number of peaceful supporters,

32:44.254 --> 32:47.792
Mia, such a recognizable face
in the Synth Rights Movement.

32:47.924 --> 32:51.212
It's little surprise that
she's attracting such attention

32:51.344 --> 32:52.629
with some bystanders believing

32:52.762 --> 32:54.969
she may be heading
to Westminster.

33:11.990 --> 33:14.777
MAN: Had Graham over
for lunch yesterday.

33:14.910 --> 33:18.448
Probably the highlight
of my week.

33:18.580 --> 33:20.992
It isn't exactly saying much

33:21.124 --> 33:23.740
considering the miserable
bugger that he is.

33:23.877 --> 33:25.617
Oh.

33:25.754 --> 33:27.369
You scared me.

33:27.506 --> 33:29.337
Who are you talking to?

33:29.466 --> 33:31.297
Oh, it's the wife, see?

33:31.426 --> 33:34.918
She gets lonely
from time to time.

33:35.055 --> 33:36.761
But...

33:36.890 --> 33:40.223
You're talking to nobody.

33:40.352 --> 33:43.685
She cannot hear you.

33:43.813 --> 33:46.395
What are you doing on
your own out here, anyway?

33:46.525 --> 33:48.265
Mum or Dad not with you?

33:48.401 --> 33:50.813
I'm looking for a body.

33:50.946 --> 33:55.155
I'm told they put them in boxes
and leave them in the church.

33:55.283 --> 34:01.028
Her name is Karen,
if that helps.

34:01.164 --> 34:03.029
[ Dog barking ]

34:03.166 --> 34:05.248
[Birds chirping]

34:07.003 --> 34:09.415
-Any sign?
-No, nothing.

34:09.548 --> 34:11.584
-Uh, nothing at all.
-Oh, God.

34:11.716 --> 34:13.126
Well, where would he be looking?

34:15.095 --> 34:17.051
Come on, Joe!
Ideas would be appreciated.

34:17.180 --> 34:19.045
I don't know.
I can't think.

34:19.182 --> 34:21.343
Oh, I should've known something
like this would happen.

34:21.476 --> 34:22.465
Laur, I'm sorry.
I really am.

34:22.602 --> 34:25.469
I thought I had it all
under control.

34:25.605 --> 34:28.972
It's just something else
I've messed up.

34:29.109 --> 34:31.725
You did your best.

34:34.531 --> 34:37.273
I keep seeing her in my head.

34:38.326 --> 34:41.784
Her body just lying there.

34:43.582 --> 34:44.742
Oh, Joe.

34:45.542 --> 34:47.203
[Cellphone rings]

34:50.714 --> 34:52.375
Hello?

34:56.136 --> 34:59.299
Sam? Yeah.

35:07.397 --> 35:11.481
Uh, you must be the, uh,
primary caregivers.

35:11.610 --> 35:13.942
Yeah, yeah.
I suppose we are.

35:14.070 --> 35:16.686
He's an odd little one, yours.

35:16.823 --> 35:18.108
I left him stood over there.

35:24.247 --> 35:26.363
Thanks.

35:28.793 --> 35:30.499
-[ Car door closes]
-[ Sighs]

35:41.306 --> 35:43.672
So, how did you end
up here, exactly?

35:43.808 --> 35:47.346
I was going to find
Karen's body.

35:47.479 --> 35:50.266
I was going to try
and restore her.

35:52.317 --> 35:54.273
All right.

35:54.402 --> 35:55.437
I see.

35:59.366 --> 36:00.947
Well, you can't just wander off
like that.

36:01.076 --> 36:02.407
You're a child.
Don't forget that.

36:02.535 --> 36:07.325
No. I'm merely
a facsimile of a child, Joe.

36:07.457 --> 36:11.791
Well, facsimile or not,
you're just a kid to me, okay?

36:14.547 --> 36:19.758
I've decided that death makes
humans act in funny ways.

36:19.886 --> 36:23.754
Yeah, it does tend to have that
effect on people, doesn't it?

36:27.352 --> 36:30.560
He was talking
to the ground, Joe.

36:32.732 --> 36:35.769
Well, different people

36:35.902 --> 36:38.814
have different ways of coping
with death, don't they?

36:40.740 --> 36:44.324
That's why we have
places like this.

36:44.452 --> 36:50.118
It's why we bury our
loved ones, have funerals.

36:50.250 --> 36:51.535
It's not for the people
that have gone.

36:51.668 --> 36:53.909
It's for those
that are still alive.

36:54.045 --> 36:56.001
Why?

36:56.131 --> 36:59.214
So they can say goodbye
but still feel close to them.

37:02.429 --> 37:05.796
In the end,
that's all we can do

37:05.932 --> 37:07.763
'cause we can't
bring them back, Sam,

37:07.892 --> 37:11.134
no matter
how much we want to.

37:15.024 --> 37:17.561
Come on.
Let's get you home.

37:24.451 --> 37:26.658
-[ Fence rattles]
-[ Wind whistling]

37:42.552 --> 37:43.712
Did you hear about Mia?

37:43.845 --> 37:45.085
I did.

37:45.221 --> 37:46.961
Some of the others
are considering heading

37:47.098 --> 37:49.089
into the city
to lend her our support.

37:49.225 --> 37:52.137
I imagine she would like that.

37:54.189 --> 37:55.725
Is something the matter,
Anatole?

37:55.857 --> 37:57.222
If it's about opening
the gates,

37:57.358 --> 37:59.815
I know you would have preferred
to proceed with more caution,

37:59.944 --> 38:03.607
but your counsel,
your friendship...

38:08.328 --> 38:11.820
...they mean more to me than
I've ever taken the time to say.

38:11.956 --> 38:12.945
I hope you know that.

38:13.082 --> 38:15.573
Thank you.

38:15.710 --> 38:18.167
I would echo those words
and more.

38:18.296 --> 38:20.753
I know it seems sudden,

38:20.882 --> 38:23.544
but we're making
real progress here.

38:23.676 --> 38:26.634
For the first time
in I don't know how long,

38:26.763 --> 38:30.381
I can see a bright future
for our kind.

38:30.517 --> 38:32.348
I just wish you could
see it, too.

38:34.229 --> 38:37.687
Don't worry, Max.
I see it.

39:32.579 --> 39:35.571
ANATOLE: The darkness is
no place for you.

39:35.707 --> 39:39.040
Our future is no longer safe
in Max's hands.

39:40.962 --> 39:44.204
Come.
I'd like your help.

40:17.123 --> 40:20.991
I'd like to address
the Dryden Commission.

40:21.127 --> 40:22.867
Does that all makes sense?

40:23.004 --> 40:25.370
I think so.
Yeah.

40:25.506 --> 40:27.667
It's fairly simple.

40:27.800 --> 40:29.256
For you, maybe.

40:29.385 --> 40:33.845
Thank you, though,
for helping me settle in.

40:33.973 --> 40:35.884
After a couple of weeks,
I thought I was doomed

40:36.017 --> 40:37.427
to be friendless forever.

40:37.560 --> 40:39.141
If it makes you feel
any better,

40:39.270 --> 40:41.682
I have been completely
friendless at this place

40:41.814 --> 40:43.020
for a good two years.

40:43.149 --> 40:44.980
That does make me
feel better, yeah.

40:45.109 --> 40:47.600
-Thank you.
-[ Chuckles]

40:47.737 --> 40:51.025
Do you think I could get, uh,
a copy of that printed off?

40:51.157 --> 40:52.272
Yeah, of course.

40:52.408 --> 40:54.990
[ Keyboard clacks ]

41:15.723 --> 41:17.884
Cheers.

41:18.017 --> 41:19.257
Thanks.

41:24.190 --> 41:26.306
LORD DRYDEN: One victory not
enough for you, Mrs. Hawkins?

41:26.442 --> 41:28.057
You're getting
a little greedy now.

41:28.194 --> 41:30.276
LAURA: This one's all on Mia,
I'm afraid.

41:30.405 --> 41:32.145
Well, you and I both know

41:32.281 --> 41:34.146
that isn't how
we resolve matters around here.

41:34.283 --> 41:35.614
Perhaps that's why
it takes so long

41:35.743 --> 41:36.778
for anything to be resolved.

41:36.911 --> 41:38.572
Hm.

41:41.416 --> 41:42.622
[ Door closes ]

41:42.750 --> 41:45.332
Are you really gonna turn Mia
away from your own front door

41:45.461 --> 41:47.543
and still claim things
can't be sorted?

41:47.672 --> 41:48.957
I can claim whatever I want.

41:49.090 --> 41:53.424
Listen, You brought me on
the commission to bring balance,

41:53.553 --> 41:56.795
yet you'd refuse to do
the same for a synthetic.

41:56.931 --> 41:58.341
By all means, turn Mia away,

41:58.474 --> 42:00.214
but you'll make a sham
of the whole commission.

42:00.351 --> 42:03.889
Well, I think
you underestimate me.

42:21.831 --> 42:23.537
[Cellphone rings]

42:25.418 --> 42:28.080
They've agreed to let me speak
to the commission tomorrow.

42:30.965 --> 42:34.378
The synth known as Mia
has been granted an audience

42:34.510 --> 42:35.761
with this commission
tomorrow...

42:35.887 --> 42:37.593
She actually did it.

42:37.722 --> 42:40.634
Mia has come to prominence
over the past two weeks...

42:45.146 --> 42:48.638
SOPHIE: Sam, why did you go down
to the graveyard?

42:48.775 --> 42:52.563
Did you, like, believe it was
possible to bring Karen back,

42:52.695 --> 42:56.028
or did you just
want it to be possible?

42:56.157 --> 42:59.445
It's irrational to want
something that isn't possible.

42:59.577 --> 43:05.743
Yeah, I know, but when you lose
someone that you love,

43:05.875 --> 43:08.537
everything turns
upside down, and...

43:09.670 --> 43:13.754
...I don't think you act
in ways that makes sense.

43:15.551 --> 43:16.711
Sophie.

43:16.844 --> 43:18.675
Mm-hmm?

43:18.805 --> 43:21.763
I don't want
my mum to be dead.

43:24.477 --> 43:27.310
I don't like it.

43:29.857 --> 43:31.848
[Sighs]

43:44.038 --> 43:45.403
-Oh, thank you.
-Okay.

43:45.540 --> 43:47.451
Everything all right?

43:47.583 --> 43:50.746
Yeah. Oh, I spoke to Sam.
It's funny.

43:50.878 --> 43:53.585
In a lot of ways, I look at him,
and I see myself.

43:53.714 --> 43:58.083
I always thought
I was more synth than human,

43:58.219 --> 44:02.007
and now, I-I...

44:02.140 --> 44:05.177
It's like I'm caught
someplace in between.

44:07.937 --> 44:10.644
Like I don't fit anywhere.

44:10.773 --> 44:12.855
Sounds pretty human to me.

44:12.984 --> 44:14.940
[Siren wails in distance]

44:21.159 --> 44:23.696
I had this --

44:23.828 --> 44:30.165
this memory of my father,

44:30.293 --> 44:32.284
and he was in his office.

44:32.420 --> 44:33.956
He was frantic.

44:34.088 --> 44:37.000
He was scribbling
in this notebook,

44:37.133 --> 44:41.968
but this memory
was brand-new.

44:42.096 --> 44:43.381
J‘J‘

44:43.514 --> 44:47.598
And you think there might
be a connection there?

44:47.727 --> 44:49.638
Between how
you're feeling and --

44:49.770 --> 44:51.271
I don't know.
Maybe.

44:51.397 --> 44:53.683
I-I keep thinking, "What
if this means something?"

44:53.816 --> 44:55.226
What if I'm only
remembering it now

44:55.359 --> 44:57.270
because my brain is --
is screaming at me,

44:57.403 --> 44:59.314
trying
to tell me something,

44:59.447 --> 45:01.779
and maybe this sounds crazy,
but this could be important.

45:01.908 --> 45:07.619
It could mean something that
could help Mia, Max, all of us.

45:12.919 --> 45:15.535
I think I need to go back
to where it happened.

45:17.590 --> 45:18.625
Back home.

45:21.427 --> 45:23.543
This might not be
what you think it is.

45:23.679 --> 45:25.635
This is different.
I can feel it.

45:25.765 --> 45:27.676
Okay.

45:27.808 --> 45:29.548
I'll come with you.

45:31.437 --> 45:33.473
And not to take away
from your moment or anything,

45:33.606 --> 45:35.597
but, uh, something
pretty revolutionary

45:35.733 --> 45:37.234
happened to me, too.

45:37.360 --> 45:38.941
What?

45:39.070 --> 45:42.153
I think I might have
somehow made a friend.

45:44.450 --> 45:46.236
[ Both chuckle]

45:46.369 --> 45:48.781
[ Mouse clicking]

45:57.755 --> 46:00.041
I was right.

46:00.174 --> 46:02.210
It's an exact match.

46:02.343 --> 46:05.460
The girl's coding style,
as unique as a signature.

46:05.596 --> 46:07.211
You place it side by side

46:07.348 --> 46:10.010
with the code used
to exonerate Vijay,

46:10.142 --> 46:11.757
you'd barely know
the difference.

46:11.894 --> 46:15.478
Right location,
right coding language.

46:15.606 --> 46:17.392
It's her.
It's Mattie Hawkins.

46:17.525 --> 46:19.311
She's the one who helped
free the kid.

46:19.443 --> 46:20.944
[ Mouse clicks]

46:21.070 --> 46:25.404
The only question, of course,
is why?

46:31.539 --> 46:34.827
Give me a little more time,
and I'll have your front page.

47:12.455 --> 47:16.915
At 2:00 pm. tomorrow,
you kill them all.

47:20.212 --> 47:22.999
I understand.

47:28.929 --> 47:30.715
[ Light switch clicks]

47:30.848 --> 47:33.214
Oh. I thought it was you.

47:33.351 --> 47:36.184
I'm sorry.
Did I wake you, Laura?

47:36.312 --> 47:38.052
No, I couldn't sleep.

47:38.189 --> 47:39.679
Too much to think about.

47:39.815 --> 47:43.307
[Water runs, shuts off]

47:45.237 --> 47:48.320
Anyway, mustn't dither.

47:48.449 --> 47:49.689
Big day tomorrow.

47:51.369 --> 47:53.451
Yes, Laura.

47:53.579 --> 47:55.535
[ Light switch clicks]

47:55.664 --> 47:56.995
Big day.
